Lunch special $15. 1) Fried stuffed shrimp w\/tofu, eggplant. 2) thinly sliced ribeye, tsukune, egg hot udon soup. 3) yuzu yogurt sorbet w\/ honey and berries. Yum!

Dinner menu expanded by 6-8 items with more fish options (salmon, trout, hamachi, black cod).  Hama Hama oysters were good $5\/2pc.  Nabeyaki Udon is edible art loaded with fresh seafood and delicate super hot broth

Also, most dishes are skewed towards Yuzu  (citrus) flavors, so if you're not a Yuzu fan, this may not be your spot.

If you have a few minutes to kill and a fan of the show, why not. Not worth waiting in line or anything, but fun to walk around and snap some pics. Don't expect to see anyone from the show.
Service is so indifferent and slow. Had some bad tasting scallops, told them about it, and was taken off the bill. Nice.
Never tried some things on the menu like uni and salmon\/hamachi kama because they were already out around 6:30pm. Cramped and stuffy inside. If I had a choice, I'd go with Goyemon over Yama.

Beware of the $20 daily resort fee, but it does include wi-fi in your room and gym access.
go pac man!
$22 resort fee pays for wifi, gym, newspaper that you pick up yourself. The question is, will you use it all to get your money's worth?
Standard rooms have a small fridge in the closet, below the security safe.
The best chicken fried steak! I get it with gravy on the side.
Go early right when they open, easy to find parking, less crowded, and a few degrees cooler. "Sales" aren't really sales for most. Beware.
$30 dam tour includes going through some tunnels and peeking through the vent from inside the dam. Also see earthquake sensor that you will get in huge trouble if you touch it.

They used to have more high quality selection overall, but the King crab legs seem better than I remember so get your money's worth there. Ask them to steam the crab legs for you. Ignore their gloomy face as they do it.
Skip the line if you have a Grazie card.
Corned beef hash is now called pastrami hash. Large portions, huge chunks of meat. Worth the $15.95.
10-15 minute walk to Wynn\/Encore down Desert Inn, a good sweat in the heat. Might be a "dicey" experience for some. Decent hot breakfast.
Pretty decent Chinese food, surprisingly. $50 worth of late night food, comped. Thanks Venetian!
The pastrami and corned beef egg sandwich was good, except that there was barely any meat for $12.99.
1,000 point reservation on OpenTable. For dessert, check out those "Munchkin" jelly donut holes with vanilla dipping sauce. If you feel like beef, go with Heritage Steak.
Average dim sum and the carts barely roll by. Good dessert pastries, especially when fresh. 50 cent tea charge per person.
They charge you an extra "bar fee" for sitting and dining in the bar area (on the left when you walk in), which is pretty ridiculous.
The more I eat here, the more I realize I don't really care for the fries or the toast. Just gimme a bunch of those chicken strips!
Get the seafood jackpot for 2. Loaded with oysters, jumbo shrimp, king crab, crab claws, jumbo lump crab, Maine lobster. Super fresh and meaty.
Try the "dirty" Alaskan chowder! Mixture of white and red. Loaded with shrimp, crab, lobster, it's a bargain at $18.99.
Try the bull roast. Secret menu item. Combination of pan roast and bouillabaisse. Not as heavy and creamy with regular pan roast.
Seafood jackpot now $60. Used to be $70. What a steal. Available after 5pm.
Alaskan chowder price used to be $18.99. Now it's $23.99! Still worth it since they load it with seafood, but not quite the bargain like it was before.

The toppings are scant, and the crust towards the middle is very soggy and floppy. When I did the pizza fold, everything just slid right off. I've had my fair share of Neapolitan pizza all over NY and New Haven, and love thin crust pizza. Overall, the crust is a bit TOO elastic.
Middle of the pack steakhouse in city full of great steakhouses. Complimentary duck fat fries a nice touch, but the caramel popcorn given after the meal was stale. Steak was okay.
Good amount of corned beef, but it's dry and flavorless. I wish I was eating an Earl's sandwich.
Great locals casino with food court and movie theater inside. Decent dining options, but missing a good AYCE buffet.
Don't pay the asking rate. Priceline it.
Avoid the corned beef hash. It's not really corned beef. Some sort of flavorless thin meat cut in strips.
If you're in a meatball mood, try the cannonball sandwich.
Long lines now during peak hours, but it goes by fast. Jump to front of line if you flash your total rewards card.
A must visit for every Vegas trip. Walked from TI to Planet Hollywood just for these hot sammies. Sounds like a close walk, but it's not.
Call in your order ahead of time.... Eating these sandwiches while driving home (ahem, safely) is a must.
Don't give this place a bad review because you "don't get all the hype." Would you give a different rating if you didn't read reviews?
Palazzo definitely more mellow and low key than than the more happening and louder Venetian. Palazzo tables area are more spacious.

Make no mistake about it, you are paying dearly for the name. American Angus Kobe ribeye was excellent, but small portion for the price. Stay away from the sauces for your steak. Lobster was simply prepared, but tender with plenty of meat.

So much for a quiet getaway on Saturday night. Front desk said our room facing the mountain would be quiet vs. the Strip view. Nope, it's all night thumping to the same ass beat by the DJ. I'm fist pumping in my sleep.
Love the corned beef and hash for breakfast here. Sausage links are really good too. 4 pc for $5.95, pricey, but darn tasty.
If the bakery section is closed, you can order to-go from the bar area.
Get your $6 bagel and sticky bun here! Crazy mark up here, that's for sure. Save yourself and walk over to Grand Luxe Cafe for upscale "cafe" grub.
Tell them you're celebrating a birthday or anniversary and they'll send you a plate of chocolate covered strawberries and macaroons on the house.
Been here 4 times now, prices have gone way up since the start. It's a bit overrated, only worth it if you eat lots of hot crab legs.
Try the root beer on tap, then get a scoop of vanilla "gelato" (tastes like ice cream) for a root beer float.

This buffet isn't as popular nor a bargain anymore. $40 for weekend seafood lunch\/dinner is only worth it if you gorge on crab legs, seafood, prime rib, drink alcohol. Quality has declined - they offer those skinny half snow crab legs now.
Foie gras creme brûlée was rich, creamy, decadent. But my favorite dish of the tasting menu was the 48 hour beef belly. A little bit of smokiness, sweetness, and marbling was oohhh sooo good.
Get your money's worth on the steamed crab legs and prime rib.
Best fancy and expensive Chinese restaurant on the Strip, by far. Well executed, especially the signature dishes. Skip the cocktails and dessert and save the $$$$ for the food.
Extremely overpriced, even by Vegas standards. But those lollipop buffalo wings were fantastic. Crispy and juicy.
The items featured on sale are really good prices. Some regular items, not so much.
Wash down fried oysters po boy with a bottle of Abita beer. Cool people, owner will give you tips about what to eat in New Orleans if first time visitor.
With so many dishes on the menu, there's bound to be some hits and misses. If you're deciding between the short rib and the oxtail, go with the oxtail.
Great alternative to the usual breakfast spots around town. Ask for the available flavors of quiche. Can be a bit of a wait if busy but worth it.
AT-AT walker inside the store originally can from old FAO Schwartz at Forum Shops Caesars Palace.

This off-Strip, hole in a wall is a cheaper, fresher, and less greasy version of Kogi. The food doesn't quite pack the punch, but it's not overly heavy or salty. Super friendly staff and awesome prices!
Best ramen I've had, including LA\/OC. Order extra noodles for $1.50. I like the regular curly noodles better than the thin noodles.
Can't go wrong with a runny fried egg on the Tamago burger. But along with their "crack" fries, everything was heavily salted.
Fried spinach salad a bit on the greasy side, but worth trying once.

Kiosk at the front is closed indefinitely. They said there are plans for remodel or expansion. You can still buy the tasty $5 chocolate walnut cookie inside the bar and take it to go. But not as convenient for those impulse buys... Boo!
Great street tacos and a bargain at around $2 each. The adobado is a must.
Adobo fried rice omelette is the perfect hangover food in the morning. If the wait is over half hour, order to go and you should get your food in about 15 minutes. 4 stars.
This whole gourmet, overpriced burger craze is ridiculous. Salmon burger was ok. The restaurant, mainly bar area, smells like a wet rag.
Strategically place all the little plates and mini pots like a puzzle to prevent sliding and spillage.
$20 pre fixed lunch menu, but $10 extra for either grilled octopus or crab cake. Service can be slow and indifferent.
Make sure you fold the pizza slice when eating, even if it means scalding the roof of your mouth. Please, no forks or knives!
Avoid the pizza sitting out that has to be reheated. Ask what is fresh in the oven.
Prices have gone up about a buck per slice back when they first opened. $4 per for a pepperoni, I guess still not bad by Vegas standards.
Everyone knows about the $1 oysters during happy hour. But don't forget about the $1.50 sliders!
Location closed. I will miss the $1 oysters for happy hour.
Even with discount, not worth the money. You're better off spending more on a real Cirque du Soleil and comedy show. Or, just be drunk.
Good AYCE sushi place. You'll be surprised how much and how fast you will fill up.
Located in a random strip mall. If you are unsure what to order, just ask. Order a variety, as dishes start to taste the same. Thumbs up.
Severely overpriced. Felt like I was walking around someone's musky old basement or attic with a bunch of cluttered childhood toys and junk that nobody wants.
Tried 2 desserts and the yuzu soda. The only thing memorable was that drink, perfect for the hot and dry weather.
Lobster roll has good flavor and decent amount of meat, bun is buttered and toasted. Ask for free sample of Lobster ice cream (eehhhh).
If you're craving some Italian food with a Japanese twist and something lighter and healthier than the typical cheesy mess, this place is it. The prix fixe menu is a good deal. 4 stars.
The best thing I had here were the beef short ribs, tender and not over smoked.
I agree with the consensus for the most part - good dim sum, but spotty service. Prices are actually not too bad, but $1 for tea per person (ugh).
Good ramen, but not as good as Monta -- they set the bar pretty high.
For a high end steakhouse, they have the weakest, smallest, and dullest steak knives. They are more like butter knives!
Love that al dente, chewy and firm texture from the soba noodles, especially cold. Portions are not very big relative to the prices.
One of the better croissants I've had. Try the bacon jalapeño cheddar, almond, and guava if available.
Fantastic sushi experience sitting at the bar. Nigiri omakase a great deal, but if you want more it quickly adds up. Favorites were the medium\/premium fatty tuna (toro) and uni.
Carne asada nachos, hold the sour cream and beans please.
Long wait before and after sitting during peak hours, but worth it. Fresh, quality food but coffee is pretty weak. Corned beef hash and pancakes are on on point!
Every buffet has its pros and cons. If you're a Vegas buffet veteran, I don't think you'll see or eat anything out of the ordinary here. Lines are long now, because it's the new kid on the block.
4 hour wait according to their new ticket machine. Are you serious?! They essentially force you to pay the $20 expedited fee just to get in right away. What a rip off!!

Compared to when I first tried this buffet when it first opened 2 years ago, quality, selection, and presentation has gone downhill for sure. Still only worth the price if you load up on meat and seafood.
For those who have seen other Cirque shows and those traveling circus acts, you won't really see anything new at Zarkana. It's a Vegas version with big production and set pieces.
Really good millecrepe cakes, I liked the green tea with red bean inside. Yuzu panna cotta is great if you like tart desserts.
Burger extravaganza last night was awesome. Plenty of burgers, dessert, and alcoholic beverages... and I got to meet Adam Richman. Thanks Misti and Yelp LV!
Finished judging pork and sauce today. Ribs and brisket tomorrow!

Decent "gourmet" donuts for the price. I'm used to paying $3-4 per gourmet donut in LA\/OC, and here it is $1.75. While good, the donuts aren't as light -- they are a bit heavier and dense. But still good. 4 stars.

A must see for any MJ fan who knows the music and dance moves. More of an inspiring tribute performance\/spectacular, so don't expect to see the usual Cirque stuff. Worth the splurge to get middle section seats.
Good, bubbly crust. But there's something about NY-style Secret Pizza in Cosmo that tastes better. $5.50 per slice, limited topping options.

Top AYCE sushi spot based on quality of fish, fish to rice ratio, selection, and value. Not expecting stellar service, but the waiters for my table were miserable.
Something not too sweet and perfect combo -- green tea with red beans.
Very heavy handed with the flat leaf parsley on some dishes, to the point where it just overpowers the entire dish. Had to scrape a lot off.

The chargrilled wood flavor is great on steaks, but with some delicate protein like scallops there can be a bitter burnt aftertaste -- especially when used with a glaze with sugar. When we told them, they said "the chef intended it to be that way." Uh, no.
Grand opening Monday, August 19th.
Awesome happy hour! $5 per dish. Good for a "light" seafood dinner.

If you don't see anything you like, ask them. They have more artwork because there's no more room in the gallery.
It's alright for Vegas and they do good "fusion" appetizers, but I've had better pho elsewhere. Not much depth in the broth and the oxtail meat was bland and not tender. 3 stars.

Healthy option after hiking at Red Rock!

Horrible. Avoid at all costs. Ordering system is disorganized and slow. We got stuff in the box we didn't order. They should show you the items before wrapping up the box. Everything we had was stale, flavorless, and dry. Cake boss? Cake weak sauce!

Food is more "in-yo-face" style than substance... sorta just like Guy Fieri himself. Be prepared to open your wallet for bar food.

Nice spot for some gelato and crepes. Super friendly and helpful staff. Parking can be a challenge in this plaza during peak hours.
A hidden gem. Every dish was excellent! Octopus was one of the best I've had. Scallops were perfectly cooked. Wagyu skewer was super tender.
Horrible. You're better off walking to Grand Lux Cafe at Venetian\/Palazzo.

The fried chicken was moist, juicy, flavorful. The skin wasn't as crispy as I had hoped. Not worth the $26 splurge for 4 pieces.
The fried chicken was moist, juicy, flavorful. The skin wasn't as crispy as I had hoped. Not worth the $26 splurge for 4 pieces.

They already jacked up the prices a couple bucks since they opened about a year ago ($8 per slice w\/ topping). Quality has gone down dramatically. Soggy crust. Go to Secret Pizza in Cosmo.

Good donuts in the area that are not overpriced and hipster.

Good, but I give the edge to Shang's. The noodle doesn't have that chewy, al dente texture.

Single order of wings (9pc) is enough for two people. Wings are meaty and crispy. Love the lemon pepper. 4 stars.

Super crispy chicken katsu and super chargrilled flavor from the teriyaki chicken! Goes well with mac salad and kimchi. Great value.
Quality meats! Good value for the combos, although additional items like rice and corn cheese are extra.
Solid place for semi upscale seafood. A bit pricey for a local spot, but not quite Strip pricing. Love the octopus carpaccio!

Same owners as Monta, but not as good. It's more expensive, and they only give you one measly piece of chashu. The spicy flavor overpowers the overall subtlety of the broth. Plus the scallions should be chopped up!
Beef combo for two is plenty of food. High quality meat and great service. Side dishes are really good. It's a toss up between this place and Hobak for best KBBQ in Vegas.
Showed up at lunch and the line out the door and didn't budge for 10 minutes. The cashier was nowhere in sight, busy helping expediting food. Too slow so I left.

Good, old school Hawaiian food. Seems better for dine in versus takeout. Pricier than some of the other newer Hawaiian spots in the area.

Love the broth and hand pulled noodles. Lots of quality beef too. Thumbs up. Wait staff can be slow, though, during busy hours.

The broth from the seafood toban yaki is so good! As for the sushi and sashimi, it was okay. On par with the Strip. You can get better value and quality off Strip.
